# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aws-ecs
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aws-ecs/container-virtualization] In software engineering, **containerization** is operating-system-level virtualization or application-level virtualization over multiple resources so that software applications can run in isolated user spaces called *containers* in any cloud or non-cloud environment, regardless of type or vendor.
[src:aws-ecs/container-virtualization] The term "container" has different meanings in different contexts, and it is important to ensure that the intended definition aligns with the audience's understanding.
[src:aws-ecs/container-virtualization] Each *container* is basically a fully functional and portable cloud or non-cloud computing environment surrounding the application and keeping it independent of other environments running in parallel.
[src:aws-ecs/container-virtualization] Individually, each container simulates a different software application and runs isolated processes by bundling related configuration files, libraries and dependencies.
[src:aws-ecs/container-virtualization] But, collectively, multiple containers share a common operating system kernel (OS).
[src:aws-ecs/container-virtualization] In recent times, containerization technology has been widely adopted by cloud computing platforms like Amazon Web Services, Microsoft Azure, Google Cloud Platform, and IBM Cloud.
[src:aws-ecs/container-virtualization] Containerization has also been pursued by the U.S.
[src:aws-ecs/container-virtualization] Department of Defense as a way of more rapidly developing and fielding software updates, with first application in its F-22 air superiority fighter.
[src:aws-ecs/container-virtualization] Container orchestration or container management is mostly used in the context of application containers.
[src:aws-ecs/container-virtualization] Implementations providing such orchestration include Kubernetes and Docker swarm.
[src:aws-ecs/container-virtualization] This includes functionality to create a cluster, to upgrade the software or repair it, balance the load between existing instances, scale by starting or stopping instances to adapt to the number of users, to log activities and monitor produced logs or the application itself by querying sensors.
[src:aws-ecs/container-virtualization] Open-source implementations of such software include OKD and Rancher.
[src:aws-ecs/container-virtualization] Quite a number of companies provide container cluster management as a managed service, like Alibaba, Amazon, Google, and Microsoft.
[src:aws-ecs/docker-software] The core software that runs and manages these containers is called **Docker Engine**.
[src:aws-ecs/docker-software] Docker was first released in 2013 and continues to be developed by Docker, Inc.
[src:aws-ecs/docker-software] The platform includes both free and paid tiers.
[src:aws-ecs/docker-software] Solomon Hykes started the Docker project in France as an internal project within dotCloud, a platform-as-a-service company.
[src:aws-ecs/docker-software] dotCloud Inc. was founded by Kamel Founadi, Hykes, and Sebastien Pahl during the Y Combinator Summer 2010 startup incubator group and launched in 2011, and renamed to Docker Inc in 2013.
[src:aws-ecs/docker-software] Docker debuted to the public in Santa Clara at PyCon in 2013.
[src:aws-ecs/docker-software] It was released as open-source in March 2013.
[src:aws-ecs/docker-software] At the time, it used LXC as its default execution environment.
[src:aws-ecs/docker-software] One year later, with the release of version 0.9, Docker replaced LXC with its own component, *libcontainer*, which was written in the Go programming language.
[src:aws-ecs/docker-software] In 2017, Docker created the Moby project for open research and development.
[src:aws-ecs/docker-software] In March 2026, the Communications of the ACM featured Docker as the cover article in a retrospective article of the past decade.
[src:aws-ecs/docker-software] Containers are isolated from one another and bundle their own software, libraries and configuration files; they can communicate with each other through well-defined channels.
[src:aws-ecs/docker-software] Because all of the containers share the services of a single operating system kernel, they use fewer resources than virtual machines.
[src:aws-ecs/docker-software] Docker can package an application and its dependencies in a virtual container that can, in principle, run on any Linux, Windows, or macOS computer.
[src:aws-ecs/docker-software] This enables the application to run in a variety of locations, such as on-premises, in public *(see decentralized computing, distributed computing, and cloud computing)* or private cloud.
[src:aws-ecs/docker-software] Docker on macOS uses a Linux virtual machine to run the containers.
[src:aws-ecs/docker-software] Because Docker containers are lightweight, a single server or virtual machine can run several containers simultaneously.
[src:aws-ecs/docker-software] A 2018 analysis found that a typical Docker use case involves running eight containers per host, and that a quarter of analyzed organizations run 18 or more per host.
[src:aws-ecs/docker-software] It can also be installed on a single board computer like the Raspberry Pi.
[src:aws-ecs/docker-software] The Linux kernel's support for namespaces mostly isolates an application's view of the operating environment, including process trees, network, user IDs and mounted file systems, while the kernel's cgroups provide resource limiting for memory and CPU.
[src:aws-ecs/docker-software] Since version 0.9, Docker includes its own component (called libcontainer) to use virtualization facilities provided directly by the Linux kernel, in addition to using abstracted virtualization interfaces via libvirt, LXC and systemd-nspawn.
[src:aws-ecs/docker-software] Docker implements a high-level API to provide lightweight containers that run processes in isolation.
[src:aws-ecs/docker-software] , is a persistent process that manages Docker containers and handles container objects.
[src:aws-ecs/docker-software] The daemon listens for requests that are sent via the Docker Engine API.
[src:aws-ecs/docker-software] (CLI) that allows users to interact with Docker daemons.
[src:aws-ecs/docker-software] Docker objects are various entities used to assemble an application in Docker.
[src:aws-ecs/docker-software] The main classes of Docker objects are images, containers, and services.
[src:aws-ecs/docker-software] A Docker registry is a repository for Docker images.
[src:aws-ecs/docker-software] Docker clients connect to registries to download ("pull") images for use or upload ("push") images that they have built.
[src:aws-ecs/docker-software] Docker Hub is the default registry where Docker looks for images.
[src:aws-ecs/docker-software] Docker registries also allow the creation of notifications based on events.
[src:aws-ecs/docker-software] A Dockerfile is a text file that commonly specifies several aspects of a Docker container: the Linux distribution, installation commands for the programming language runtime environment and application source code.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] In software engineering, a **microservice** architecture is an architectural pattern that organizes an application into a collection of loosely coupled, fine-grained services that communicate through lightweight protocols.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] This pattern allows teams to develop, deploy, and scale services independently, improving modularity, scalability, and adaptability.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] However, it introduces additional complexity, particularly in managing distributed systems and inter-service communication, making the initial implementation more challenging compared to a monolithic architecture.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] There is no single, universally agreed-upon definition of microservices.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] However, they are generally characterized by a focus on modularity, with each service designed around a specific business capability.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] These services are loosely coupled, independently deployable, and often developed and scaled separately, enabling greater flexibility and agility in managing complex systems.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] Microservices architecture is closely associated with principles such as domain-driven design, decentralization of data and governance, and the flexibility to use different technologies for individual services to best meet their requirements.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] It is common for microservices architectures to be adopted for cloud-native applications, serverless computing, and applications using lightweight container deployment via OS-level virtualization.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] According to Fowler, because of the large number (when compared to monolithic application implementations) of services, decentralized continuous delivery and DevOps with holistic service monitoring are necessary to effectively develop, maintain, and operate such applications.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] A consequence of (and rationale for) following this approach is that the individual microservices can be individually scaled.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] In the monolithic approach, an application supporting three functions would have to be scaled in its entirety even if only one of these functions had a resource constraint.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] With microservices, only the microservice supporting the function with resource constraints needs to be scaled out, thus providing resource and cost optimization benefits.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] Despite its benefits, microservices architecture introduces challenges such as increased operational complexity, network latency, and the need for robust monitoring and fault tolerance mechanisms.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] Cell-based architecture is a distributed computing design in which computational resources are organized into self-contained units called cells.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] Each cell operates independently, handling a subset of requests while maintaining scalability, fault isolation, and availability.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] A cell typically consists of multiple microservices and functions as an autonomous unit.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] In some implementations, entire sets of microservices are replicated across multiple cells, enabling requests to be rerouted to another operational cell if one experiences a failure.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] This approach is intended to improve system-wide resilience by limiting the impact of localized failures.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] Some implementations incorporate circuit breakers within and between cells.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] Within a cell, circuit breakers may be used to mitigate cascading failures among microservices, while inter-cell circuit breakers can isolate failing cells and redirect traffic to those that remain operational.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] Cell-based architecture has been adopted in certain large-scale distributed systems where fault isolation and redundancy are design priorities.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] Its implementation varies based on system requirements, infrastructure constraints, and specific operational goals.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] In 1999, software developer Peter Rodgers had been working on the Dexter research project at Hewlett Packard Labs, whose aim was to make code less brittle and to make large-scale, complex software systems robust to change.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] Ultimately this path of research led to the development of resource-oriented computing (ROC), a generalized computation abstraction in which REST is a special subset.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] In 2005, during a presentation at the Web Services Edge conference, Rodgers argued for "REST-services" and stated that "Software components are Micro-Web-Services...
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] Micro-Services are composed using Unix-like pipelines (the Web meets Unix = true loose-coupling).
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] Services can call services (+multiple language run-times).
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] Complex service assemblies are abstracted behind simple URI interfaces.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] Also in 2005, Alistair Cockburn wrote about hexagonal architecture which is a software design pattern that is used along with the microservices.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] This pattern makes the design of the microservice possible since it isolates in layers the business logic from the auxiliary services needed in order to deploy and run the microservice completely independent from others.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] Determining the appropriate level of (micro)service granularity in a microservices architecture often requires iterative collaboration between architects and developers.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] This process involves evaluating user requirements, service responsibilities, and architectural characteristics, such as non-functional requirements.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] Neal Ford highlights the role of integrator and disintegrator factors in this context.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] Integrator factors, such as shared transactions or tightly coupled processes, favor combining services, while disintegrator factors, such as fault tolerance or independent scalability, encourage splitting services to meet operational and architectural goals.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] Additionally, fitness functions, as proposed by Neal Ford, can be used to validate architectural decisions and service granularity by continuously measuring system qualities or behaviors that are critical to stakeholders, ensuring alignment with overall architectural objectives.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] In microservices architectures, service granularity influences testing, deployment, performance, and reliability.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] Very fine-grained microservices are typically easier to test and deploy independently, but they often experience lower performance and reduced overall reliability due to increased interservice communication and more complex service choreography.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] Coarse-grained services exhibit contrasting characteristics.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] They generally provide higher robustness and reliability by minimizing communication overhead and coordination complexity, but they are more challenging to test and deploy because modifications affect a broader functional scope.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] The appropriate level of service granularity is determined by business drivers.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] Architectural decisions commonly begin with identifying these drivers and then aligning architectural characteristics such as performance, scalability, reliability, or deployment flexibility to support them.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] A bounded context, a fundamental concept in domain-driven design (DDD), defines a specific area within which a domain model is consistent and valid, ensuring clarity and separation of concerns.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] In microservices architecture, a bounded context often maps to a microservice, but this relationship can vary depending on the design approach.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] A one-to-one relationship, where each bounded context is implemented as a single microservice, is typically ideal as it maintains clear boundaries, reduces coupling, and enables independent deployment and scaling.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] The choice of relationship should balance the principles of DDD with the system's business goals, technical constraints, and operational requirements.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] The architecture introduces additional complexity and new problems to deal with, such as latency, message format design, backup/availability/consistency (BAC), load balancing and fault tolerance.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] All of these problems have to be addressed at scale.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] The complexity of a monolithic application does not disappear if it is re-implemented as a set of microservices.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] Some of the complexity gets translated into operational complexity.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] Other places where the complexity manifests itself are increased network traffic and slower performance.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] Also, an application made up of any number of microservices has a larger number of interface points to access its respective ecosystem, which increases the architectural complexity.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] Various organizing principles (such as hypermedia as the engine of application state (HATEOAS), interface and data model documentation captured via Swagger, etc.) have been applied to reduce the impact of such additional complexity.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] Microservices are susceptible to the fallacies of distributed computing – a series of misconceptions that can lead to significant issues in software development and deployment.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] Ideally, microservices follow a "share-nothing" architecture.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] However, in practice, microservices architectures often encounter situations where code must be shared across services.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] Each approach has its advantages and trade-offs, depending on the specific context and requirements.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] Richards & Ford in *Fundamentals of software architecture* (2020) propose each microservice should have its own architectural characteristics (a.k.a. non functional requirements), and architects should not define uniform characteristics for the entire distributed system.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] To avoid having to coordinate deployments across different microservices, Sam Newman suggests keeping the interfaces of microservices stable and making backwards-compatible changes as interfaces evolve.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] On the topic of testing, Newman in *Building Microservices* (2015) proposes consumer-driven contract testing as a better alternative to traditional end-to-end testing in the context of microservices.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] He also suggests the use of log aggregation and metrics aggregation as well as distributed tracing tools to ensure the observability of systems composed of microservices.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] Computer microservices can be implemented in different programming languages and might use different infrastructures.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] Therefore, the most important technology choices are the way microservices communicate with each other (synchronous, asynchronous, UI integration) and the protocols used for the communication (e.g.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] In a traditional system, most technology choices like the programming language impact the whole system.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] Therefore, the approach to choosing technologies is quite different.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] The Eclipse Foundation has published a specification for developing microservices, Eclipse MicroProfile.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] In a service mesh, each service instance is paired with an instance of a reverse proxy server, called a service proxy, sidecar proxy, or sidecar.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] The service instance and sidecar proxy share a container, and the containers are managed by a container orchestration tool such as Kubernetes, Docker Swarm, or DC/OS.
[src:aws-ecs/microservices] The service proxies are responsible for communication with other service instances and can support capabilities such as service (instance) discovery, load balancing, authentication and authorization, secure communications, and others.
[src:aws-ecs/orchestration-computing] In system administration, **orchestration** is the automated configuration, coordination, deployment, and management of computer systems and software.
[src:aws-ecs/orchestration-computing] Many tools exist for automating server configuration and management.
[src:aws-ecs/orchestration-computing] Orchestration is often discussed in the context of service-oriented architecture, virtualization, provisioning, converged infrastructure, and dynamic data center topics.
[src:aws-ecs/orchestration-computing] Orchestration in this sense is about aligning the business request with the applications, data, and infrastructure.
[src:aws-ecs/orchestration-computing] In the context of cloud computing, the main difference between workflow automation and orchestration is that workflows are processed and completed as processes within a single domain for automation purposes.
[src:aws-ecs/orchestration-computing] Orchestration, meanwhile, incorporates workflows and provides a directed action towards larger goals and objectives.
[src:aws-ecs/orchestration-computing] In the context of application programming interfaces (APIs), API orchestration refers to the process of integrating multiple APIs into a unified system to streamline workflows and enhance user experience.
[src:aws-ecs/orchestration-computing] The approach coordinates the flow of data, the execution sequence, and the dependencies among different APIs to achieve a defined business objective.
[src:aws-ecs/orchestration-computing] API orchestration is commonly applied in environments that utilize microservices architectures or legacy systems, where the interaction of several APIs is required to complete a task.
[src:aws-ecs/os-level-virtualization] On Unix-like operating systems, this feature can be seen as an advanced implementation of the standard chroot mechanism, which changes the apparent root folder for the current running process and its children.
[src:aws-ecs/os-level-virtualization] In addition to isolation mechanisms, the kernel often provides resource-management features to limit the impact of one container's activities on other containers.
[src:aws-ecs/os-level-virtualization] Linux containers are all based on the virtualization, isolation, and resource management mechanisms provided by the Linux kernel, notably Linux namespaces and cgroups.
[src:aws-ecs/os-level-virtualization] Although the word *container* most commonly refers to OS-level virtualization, it is sometimes used to refer to fuller virtual machines operating in varying degrees of concert with the host OS, such as Microsoft's Hyper-V containers.
[src:aws-ecs/os-level-virtualization] For an overview of virtualization since 1960, see Timeline of virtualization technologies.
[src:aws-ecs/os-level-virtualization] On ordinary operating systems for personal computers, a computer program can see (even though it might not be able to access) all the system's resources.
[src:aws-ecs/os-level-virtualization] The operating system may allow or deny access to such resources based on which program requests them and the user account in the context in which it runs.
[src:aws-ecs/os-level-virtualization] The operating system may also hide those resources, so that when the computer program enumerates them, they do not appear in the enumeration results.
[src:aws-ecs/os-level-virtualization] Nevertheless, from a programming point of view, the computer program has interacted with those resources and the operating system has managed an act of interaction.
[src:aws-ecs/os-level-virtualization] With operating-system-virtualization, or containerization, it is possible to run programs within containers, to which only parts of these resources are allocated.
[src:aws-ecs/os-level-virtualization] A program expecting to see the whole computer, once run inside a container, can only see the allocated resources and believes them to be all that is available.
[src:aws-ecs/os-level-virtualization] Several containers can be created on each operating system, to each of which a subset of the computer's resources is allocated.
[src:aws-ecs/os-level-virtualization] Each container may contain any number of computer programs.
[src:aws-ecs/os-level-virtualization] These programs may run concurrently or separately, and may even interact with one another.
[src:aws-ecs/os-level-virtualization] Containerization has similarities to application virtualization: In the latter, only one computer program is placed in an isolated container and the isolation applies to file system only.
[src:aws-ecs/os-level-virtualization] Operating-system level virtualization is commonly used in virtual hosting environments, where it is useful for securely allocating finite hardware resources among a large number of mutually-distrusting users.
[src:aws-ecs/os-level-virtualization] System administrators may also use it for consolidating server hardware by moving services on separate hosts into containers on the one server.
[src:aws-ecs/os-level-virtualization] Operating-system level virtualization can also be used to run software created for a certain Linux distribution on another distribution, an example is Distrobox.
[src:aws-ecs/os-level-virtualization] Other typical scenarios include separating several programs to separate containers for improved security, hardware independence, and added resource management features.
[src:aws-ecs/os-level-virtualization] The improved security provided by the use of a chroot mechanism, however, is not perfect.
[src:aws-ecs/os-level-virtualization] Operating-system-level virtualization implementations capable of live migration can also be used for dynamic load balancing of containers between nodes in a cluster.
[src:aws-ecs/os-level-virtualization] This form of virtualization also does not require hardware support for efficient performance.
[src:aws-ecs/os-level-virtualization] Operating-system level virtualization is not as flexible as other virtualization approaches since it cannot host a guest operating system different from the host one, or a different guest kernel.
[src:aws-ecs/os-level-virtualization] For example, with Linux, different distributions are fine, but other operating systems such as Windows cannot be hosted.
[src:aws-ecs/os-level-virtualization] Operating systems using variable input systematics are subject to limitations within the virtualized architecture.
[src:aws-ecs/os-level-virtualization] Adaptation methods including cloud-server relay analytics maintain the OS-level virtual environment within these applications.
[src:aws-ecs/os-level-virtualization] Solaris partially overcomes the limitation described above with its branded zones feature, which provides the ability to run an environment within a container that emulates an older Solaris 8 or 9 version in a Solaris 10 host.
[src:aws-ecs/os-level-virtualization] However, in 2010 Linux branded zones were removed from Solaris; in 2014 they were reintroduced in Illumos, which is the open source Solaris fork, supporting 32-bit Linux kernels.
[src:aws-ecs/os-level-virtualization] Some implementations provide file-level copy-on-write (CoW) mechanisms.
[src:aws-ecs/os-level-virtualization] (Most commonly, a standard file system is shared between partitions, and those partitions that change the files automatically create their own copies.) This is easier to back up, more space-efficient and simpler to cache than the block-level copy-on-write schemes common on whole-system virtualizers.
[src:aws-ecs/os-level-virtualization] Whole-system virtualizers, however, can work with non-native file systems and create and roll back snapshots of the entire system state.
[src:aws-ecs/serverless-computing] Serverless computing does not eliminate complexity but shifts much of it from the operations team to the development team.
[src:aws-ecs/serverless-computing] However, this shift is not absolute, as operations teams continue to manage aspects such as identity and access management (IAM), networking, security policies, and cost optimization.
[src:aws-ecs/serverless-computing] Additionally, while breaking down applications into finer-grained components can increase management complexity, the relationship between granularity and management difficulty is not strictly linear.
[src:aws-ecs/serverless-computing] There is often an optimal level of modularization where the benefits outweigh the added management overhead.
[src:aws-ecs/serverless-computing] According to Yan Cui, serverless techniques should be adopted only when they help to deliver customer value faster.
[src:aws-ecs/serverless-computing] And while adopting, organizations should take small steps and de-risk along the way.
[src:aws-ecs/serverless-computing] Serverless applications are prone to fallacies of distributed computing.
[src:aws-ecs/serverless-computing] Monitoring and debugging serverless applications can present unique challenges due to their distributed, event-driven nature and proprietary environments.
[src:aws-ecs/serverless-computing] Traditional tools may fall short, making it difficult to track execution flows across services.
[src:aws-ecs/serverless-computing] However, modern solutions such as distributed tracing tools (e.g., AWS X-Ray, Datadog), centralized logging, and cloud-agnostic observability platforms are mitigating these challenges.
[src:aws-ecs/serverless-computing] Emerging technologies like OpenTelemetry, AI-powered anomaly detection, and serverless-specific frameworks are further improving visibility and root cause analysis.
[src:aws-ecs/serverless-computing] While challenges persist, advancements in monitoring and debugging tools are steadily addressing these limitations.
[src:aws-ecs/serverless-computing] According to OWASP, serverless applications are vulnerable to variations of traditional attacks, insecure code, and some serverless-specific attacks (like *denial of wallet*).
[src:aws-ecs/serverless-computing] So, the risks have changed and attack prevention requires a shift in mindset.
[src:aws-ecs/serverless-computing] Serverless computing is provided as a third-party service.
[src:aws-ecs/serverless-computing] Applications and software that run in the serverless environment are by default locked to a specific cloud vendor.
[src:aws-ecs/serverless-computing] This issue is exacerbated in serverless computing, as with its increased level of abstraction, public vendors only allow customers to upload code to a FaaS platform without the authority to configure underlying environments.
[src:aws-ecs/serverless-computing] More importantly, when considering a more complex workflow that includes backend-as-a-service (BaaS), a BaaS offering can typically only natively trigger a FaaS offering from the same provider.
[src:aws-ecs/serverless-computing] This makes the workload migration in serverless computing virtually impossible.
[src:aws-ecs/serverless-computing] Therefore, considering how to design and deploy serverless workflows from a multi-cloud perspective could mitigate this.
[src:aws-ecs/serverless-computing] Serverless computing may not be ideal for certain high-performance computing (HPC) workloads due to resource limits often imposed by cloud providers, including maximum memory, CPU, and runtime restrictions.
[src:aws-ecs/serverless-computing] For workloads requiring sustained or predictable resource usage, bulk-provisioned servers can sometimes be more cost-effective than the pay-per-use model typical of serverless platforms.
[src:aws-ecs/serverless-computing] However, serverless computing is increasingly capable of supporting specific HPC workloads, particularly those that are highly parallelizable and event-driven, by leveraging its scalability and elasticity.
[src:aws-ecs/serverless-computing] The suitability of serverless computing for HPC continues to evolve with advancements in cloud technologies.
[src:aws-ecs/serverless-computing] The *grain of sand* anti-pattern refers to the creation of excessively small components (e.g., functions) within a system, often resulting in increased complexity, operational overhead, and performance inefficiencies.
[src:aws-ecs/serverless-computing] *Lambda pinball* is a related anti-pattern that can occur in serverless architectures when functions (e.g., AWS Lambda, Azure functions) excessively invoke each other in fragmented chains, leading to latency, debugging and testing challenges, and reduced observability.
[src:aws-ecs/serverless-computing] These anti-patterns are associated with the formation of a distributed monolith.
[src:aws-ecs/serverless-computing] These anti-patterns are often addressed through the application of clear domain boundaries, which distinguish between public and published interfaces.
[src:aws-ecs/serverless-computing] Public interfaces are technically accessible interfaces, such as methods, classes, API endpoints, or triggers, but they do not come with formal stability guarantees.
[src:aws-ecs/serverless-computing] In contrast, published interfaces involve an explicit stability contract, including formal versioning, thorough documentation, a defined deprecation policy, and often support for backward compatibility.
[src:aws-ecs/serverless-computing] Published interfaces may also require maintaining multiple versions simultaneously and adhering to formal deprecation processes when breaking changes are introduced.
[src:aws-ecs/serverless-computing] Fragmented chains of function calls are often observed in systems where serverless components (functions) interact with other resources in complex patterns, sometimes described as spaghetti architecture or a distributed monolith.
[src:aws-ecs/serverless-computing] In contrast, systems exhibiting clearer boundaries typically organize serverless components into cohesive groups, where internal public interfaces manage inter-component communication, and published interfaces define communication across group boundaries.
[src:aws-ecs/serverless-computing] This distinction highlights differences in stability guarantees and maintenance commitments, contributing to reduced dependency complexity.
[src:aws-ecs/serverless-computing] Additionally, patterns associated with excessive serverless function chaining are sometimes addressed through architectural strategies that emphasize native service integrations instead of individual functions, a concept referred to as the functionless mindset.
[src:aws-ecs/serverless-computing] However, this approach is noted to involve a steeper learning curve, and integration limitations may vary even within the same cloud vendor ecosystem.
[src:aws-ecs/serverless-computing] Reporting on serverless databases presents challenges, as retrieving data for a reporting service can either break the bounded contexts, reduce the timeliness of the data, or do both.
[src:aws-ecs/serverless-computing] This applies regardless of whether data is pulled directly from databases, retrieved via HTTP, or collected in batches.
[src:aws-ecs/serverless-computing] Mark Richards refers to this as the *reach-in reporting* anti-pattern.
[src:aws-ecs/serverless-computing] A possible alternative to this approach is for databases to asynchronously push the necessary data to the reporting service instead of the reporting service pulling it.
[src:aws-ecs/serverless-computing] While this method requires a separate contract between services and the reporting service and can be complex to implement, it helps preserve bounded contexts while maintaining a high level of data timeliness.
[src:aws-ecs/serverless-computing] Adopting DevSecOps practices can help improve the use and security of serverless technologies.
[src:aws-ecs/serverless-computing] In serverless applications, the distinction between infrastructure and business logic is often blurred, with applications typically distributed across multiple services.
[src:aws-ecs/serverless-computing] To maximize the effectiveness of testing, integration testing is emphasized for serverless applications.
[src:aws-ecs/serverless-computing] Additionally, to facilitate debugging and implementation, orchestration is used within the bounded context, while choreography is employed between different bounded contexts.
[src:aws-ecs/serverless-computing] Ephemeral resources are typically kept together to maintain high cohesion.
[src:aws-ecs/serverless-computing] However, shared resources with long spin-up times, such as AWS RDS clusters and landing zones, are often managed in separate repositories, deployment pipeline, and stacks.
